The Vicount, St. Albanes, Sapient. Vet. applieth this to the Leagues and Covenants of Princes, which by reaon of interet, are precielier oberved, than more acred ones. Natalis Comes, • ytholog. l. 3. c. 2. aith, that Styx dicovered the conpiracy of the
gods, and that therefore, perhaps Jove made that Water their obliging Oath. Aritotle, M • taphy. l. 1. c. 3. conceiveth, that the Poets by this fiction, intended to ignifie, that water is the original of all things. So Thales Mileius aid, that, water is initium rerum; Deum autem, eam Meutem quae, ex aqua cuncta fingeret, as Cicero aith, De nat. Deox. lib. 1. according to that of Moes, Gen. 1. 2. So the god's Oath eemeth to have been by the firt beginning of things. Other reaons may be een in Cal. R • odiginus, lib. 27. c. 5. Of this opinion, Plutarch heweth Homer to be, lib. De Homero, where he citeth Thales for it; and, after them, Xenophanes. The reaons of whoe conjecture, Euebius giveth, De praepar. Evang. lib. 14. c. 14. Servius in Aen. 6. aith, Acheron hath its name, qua ••
